<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="162" type="">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="162">
I have examined the holotype (MRAC), and twenty-one paratypes (MRAC, NHML). It is not clear why 
<bibRefCitation author="Browne, FG" journalOrPublisher="Revue de Zoologie Africaine" pageId="7" pageNumber="164" pagination="773 - 779" title="Some new species of Scolytidae and Platypodidae from Africa and the Seychelles Islands." volume="94" year="1980">Browne (1980)</bibRefCitation>
assigned this species to the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Cryphalus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cryphalus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cryphalus</taxonomicName>
Erichson. Such an assignment within the tribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="5" pageNumber="162" rank="tribe" tribe="Cryphalini">Cryphalini</taxonomicName>
is ruled out by the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="sixâ€“segmented">six-segmented</normalizedToken>
funicle, the elongate eyes, the lack of a visible scutellum, the raised and crenulate basal margin of the elytra, and other characters. The species is here removed from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Cryphalus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cryphalus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cryphalus</taxonomicName>
and transferred to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hylesinopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hylesinopsis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hylesinopsis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
